tags: leave me alone i just really like big brother matt
summary: something soft, because it’s been on my mind for a while now and it won’t leave me alone: Foggy and Karen on their way to Matt’s...
body:
something soft, because it’s been on my mind for a while now and it won’t leave me alone:

Foggy and Karen on their way to Matt’s place to take him out pub crawling or something

Matt hears them coming from down the block and immediately sends foggy 2 texts:

“can’t open the door for you, use your keys”

“try not to be too loud”

foggy, worried, thinks that perhaps he has gotten badly injured as DD, so he and Karen rush to Matt’s apartment and let themselves in

only to find matt sprawled comfortably on a couch, one hand reading a book, the other carding through a head of dark hair in his lap

foggy, confused, is just gaping at his best friend in confusion

karen is the first to talk. “got a new boyfriend you didn’t tell us about, matt?”

matt grimaces. “karen, he’s 16.”

foggy, eyebrows rising to his hairline, “matt, why the hell do you have a teenager?” he whispers loudly

matt shrugs. “i’m friends with his aunt may. he likes to sleep over sometimes on nights when she has the late shift at work

foggy crosses his arms, not convinced. “he’s a big boy, shouldn’t he be fine at home alone for a couple of hours?”

matt levels an unimpressed stare in his general direction, the effect ruined when he ends up looking just over foggy’s left shoulder.

“his uncle was murdered a few months ago when a robber broke into their house”

foggy immediately looks chastised, his shoulders slumping and all the fight draining out of him. he heads to the kitchen to make some coffee for them, since obviously they won’t be going out now.

karen drops to the sofa across from matt and looks at the little form curled up next to her friend

“why isn’t he sleeping in the bed?” she asks, brows furrowed in disapproval

“he was having a sensory overload problem earlier, so he’s got earplugs in,” matt replies. “it helps him feel safe to know i’m here.”

karen melts just a little bit at that, already half smitten with the kid.

foggy’s still a little suspicious, because he knows his best friend, and knows that matt has never been the most cuddly guy, so there’s got to be something matt isn’t telling them about the kid. if he hadn’t known matt better than he knew himself, he’d think the kid was an illegitimate son or something.

the adults sit there for a few more hours, nursing cups of coffee and just talking, hanging out. it’s not how foggy thought he’d be spending the night, but it’s not bad

the kid, whose name is peter they soon find out, wakes up a few hours later to the quiet murmur of several voices. he sits up, all soft-eyed and rumpled from sleep, and foggy is suddenly worried that karen might try to kidnap him

peter smiles brightly at them as he pops out the earplugs.

“you must be foggy and karen” he says. “matt’s told me so much about you!”

they spend the next little while talking, and foggy feels his suspicion start to drift away.

matt may not be the most cuddly guy around, but peter is, and even the Devil of Hell’s kitchen doesn’t seem to be immune to his affection.

(And a couple of months later, when spider-man crashes into their, thankfully empty, office through an open window, Foggy feels dread rush through his veins because he recognizes the open worry on Matt’s face, the fierce protectiveness.

There’s only one other person who warrants that kind of response from his usually calm and collected friend, and when Matt pulls spider-man’s mask away to reveal messy brown hair and a familiar baby-face, his suspicions are confirmed.)
